  stickyNoteInfos:
  - title: Spawn Count
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -1383.472
      y: -336.7021
      width: 236
      height: 101
    contents: We're going to spawn our particles on a 2D grid. We created a vector2
      property to be able to tie the grid resolution with the number of particles
      to spawn.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Position 3D Sequential
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -1196
      y: 381
      width: 265
      height: 158
    contents: Position 3D sequential block is very useful to evenly distribute particles
      on a 1, 2, or 3-dimensional grid. In our case, we spawn particles on a 2D grid
      by setting the count X and count Y but leaving the count Z to 1. After this
      block, the particles are positioned on a 2D grid facing the Z axis.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Sample Texture 2D
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -1760
      y: 843
      width: 474
      height: 182
    contents: "The positions of our particles range from -1 to 1.\r\nWe're remapping
      this from (-1,1) to (0,1) to be able to easily sample our texture.\r\n\r\nThose
      remapped 0\u20131 positions (XY) can be used as UVs for sampling our Texture2D.\r\n\r\nWe're
      using the red channel of our texture2D to sample a color gradient.\r\n\r\nA
      max operation between our texture channels is done to create a black & white
      mask.\r\nThis 0 or 1 mask is used to set the \u201Calive\u201D attribute.\r\nThis
      attribute is a boolean-type attribute that determines whether a particle is
      alive or not.\r\nSo, in simple terms, we're killing particles based on the
      value samples from Texture2D.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 3
  - title: 'Turbulence:'
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -1494
      y: 1139
      width: 260
      height: 209
    contents: 'It''s pretty common to animate the transform of the turbulence block.
      This allows you to get an animated noise pattern and give more life and organic
      motion to your particles. You can offset the transform position or do some
      fancy rotation.



      Here, the turbulence intensity is also animated over
      the particle''s lifetime. This is why the sampled texture2D is easily recognizable
      when the particles are born and slowly get pushed away by the turbulence force.

'
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Alive
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -89.472046
      y: 554.2979
      width: 375
      height: 254
    contents: "Alive is a boolean attribute (0 or 1).\r\nParticles with a value of
      1 are alive, and setting the value to 0 kills the particles.\r\n\r\nBy default,
      if a lifetime attribute is present, the update context is responsible for updating
      the particle age and \u201Creaping /killing\u201D the particles.\r\n\r\nIf
      you select the update context, you can find two options:\r\n\r\nAge Particles:
      an implicit computation that is responsible for updating the age of particles
      (Age += deltaTime)\r\n\r\nReap Particles: Kill the particles by setting their
      alive attribute to false if their age exceeds their lifetime.\r\n"
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Conform to Sphere
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -120.472046
      y: 1503.2979
      width: 223
      height: 100
    contents: The conform to sphere block is used to attract the particles to the
      center of a sphere.
    theme: 
    textSize: Small
    colorTheme: 2
  - title: Sample 2DTexture
    position:
      serializedVersion: 2
      x: -694.47205
      y: -628.7021
      width: 707
      height: 144
    contents: 
    theme: 
    textSize: Huge
    colorTheme: 2
  categories: []
  uiBounds:
    serializedVersion: 2
    x: -1842
    y: -689
    width: 2153
    height: 3476
